# Frontend Development Rules

## General Principles
- Write concise, readable TypeScript
- Prefer functional components and hooks
- Use descriptive variable names (e.g., `isLoading`, `hasError`)
- Avoid premature optimization

## TypeScript
- Enable strict mode
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object shapes
- Use `const` assertions for literal types
- Avoid `any`; use `unknown` when type is uncertain
- Define return types for functions

## Next.js
- Use App Router and Server Components by default
- Client components only when needed (`'use client'`)
- Leverage `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, `not-found.tsx`
- Use `next/image` for images, `next/link` for navigation
- Fetch data in Server Components; avoid `useEffect` for data fetching
- Use route handlers for API endpoints

## React
- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks
- Memoize expensive computations with `useMemo`
- Use `useCallback` for functions passed as props
- Prefer composition over prop drilling
- Keep components small and focused

## CSS/Styling
- Use CSS Modules or Tailwind CSS
- Follow mobile-first responsive design
- Use CSS variables for theming
- Avoid inline styles except for dynamic values
- Use `rem`/`em` over `px` for scalability

## HTML/Accessibility
- Use semantic HTML (`<main>`, `<article>`, `<nav>`)
- Include proper ARIA labels where needed
- Ensure keyboard navigation works
- Maintain logical heading hierarchy
- Add `alt` text to all images

## File Structure
```
src/
  app/           # Routes and layouts
  components/    # Reusable UI components
  hooks/         # Custom hooks
  lib/           # Utilities and helpers
  types/         # TypeScript definitions
```

## Naming Conventions
- Components: `PascalCase.tsx`
- Hooks: `useCamelCase.ts`
- Utilities: `camelCase.ts`
- Types: `PascalCase` for interfaces

## Performance
- Lazy load components with `next/dynamic`
- Optimize images and fonts
- Minimize client-side JavaScript
- Use Suspense boundaries strategically